description.text:
This is my take on the ground skimmer / bolted frisbee / ground tripod. I have full confidence in this rig, with my biggest lens, down to my smallest. When I need to work on my belly, waiting for that perfect moment, this will save my arms the shakin' and achin' of holding up a 9lb rig. I hope someone else can use it too! The commercial options were all too expensive for my taste, so I designed this.

The size is restrained in order to fit on any bed at least 200x200mm, or 200mm diameter. The first layer goes down with a diameter of 187mm, and the skimmer is 195mm diameter at the top. Almost anyone with a standard reprap or above should be able to print this.

Printer:

Kossel

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

Anything works, so long as you get good layer adhesion. I recommend thick layers so it prints quickly!

Infill:

At least 25%. The infill takes much of the force applied by securing a head to the ground skimmer. 100% isn't necessary, but don't go too low or you'll pull the bolt through the part when you tighten your head.

Notes:

Use at least 4 top/bottom layers. This makes the bolt and head mating faces nice and strong.

Assembly

The required bolt is a common 3/8" hex head bolt, 1 1/2" in length. Every hardware store in the US has these, and they should be easily available around the world, being one of the most common SAE thread types. Not that there is any choice. Tripod heads almost universally require a 3/8-16 threaded screw/bolt.

Clean any errant strands of filament out of the bolt hole, and slide the bolt into place. Add a tripod head to the skimmer, and tighten it firmly. Now flip it back over, and fill the space above the bolt head with hot glue. Silicon sealant would be fine too. When the glue/sealant dries/cures, use a razor blade to slice the excess material flush with the bottom of the ground skimmer.

That's it! Go use your new ground tripod thingie! The birds will never know you are there, and your arms won't get exhausted after 5 minutes.

title: Steppers mount for P3steel with Diamond hotend

description.text:
Printed part of a mount for 3 steppers
Designed to hold the three steppers of the Diamond hotend using the center holes of the steel frame. Steppers are angled 45 degrees to each other to make it easier for the filament to get inside (using 3 spools held in parallel on the frame).
To fit the frame with this measures: 50mm wide and 3mm deep.
The holes are located in the middle width of the frame (25mm) and have a separation o 42.5 mm.
The steppers fit loosely so that a padding material can be added to reduce vibration and hold the steppers in place firmly without screwing them . (See the picture of the motor hanging upsidedown)

I used these mk9 bowden extruders without lever to avoid contact between steppers.

title: 3D-Printed Screw-In Front Lenscaps With Optional QR Code

description.text:
My thing http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:414556 was a really quick and easy 3D-printable screw-in front lenscap design, set-up as a customizer application. Less than $0.15 worth of materials are used to make a typical size lenscap, yet they work well and can even double as color references. An Instructable gives the details: http://www.instructables.com/id/3D-Printed-Screw-In-Front-Lenscaps/ .

This thing is improved in three ways (demonstrated with the green cap):

  1. This uses the new OpenSCAD font support, so you can specify the font used for labels... and you can now have 1, 2, or 3 lines of text. This version doesn't use the Write.scad library.
  2. There is now provision to specify a turn (rotation) of the screw thread to ensure the text labels stop right-side-up when the cap is screwed-into your lens filter thread.
  3. This now integrates the QR code generator http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:258542 so that you can imprint a QR code label on the inside of your lenscap. Why do that? For starters, you could use it to ID which adapted legacy lens you're using by simply taking a photo of (or including) the lenscap whenever you swap lenses.

Although the customizer parameters are well commented, please see the Instructable, http://www.instructables.com/id/3D-Printed-Screw-In-Front-Lenscaps/ , I wrote giving the details -- especially about sizing the lenscap. Keep in mind that, although you can add a QR code now, you do not have to use a QR code. Just set the QR Name to "" to work just like the old version of this thing.

Creating STLs

The OpenSCAD file has fairly obvious, commented, parameters that can be set using the Customizer or by manual editing of the file. There are way too many useful combination possible, so no STL files are posted here -- just the OpenSCAD source.

Filament Choice

Pick a plastic that has a neutral color so you can use the lenscap as a color reference. The Rosewill Grey PLA used here is quite close to a neutral gray. White or gray PLA, or clear T-Glase, are what I'd recommend.

Printing Issues

It's a straightforward and fast print, although it does have tight precision constraints on the thread diameter and pitch. PLA tends to work better than ABS because ABS doesn't hold dimensions as well over a large diameter; I also find using no more that 40% fill gives less distortion of the parts as they cool. The 0.75mm pitch typical of filter screw threads is really much too fine to be printing on typical consumer-level printers, but this uses a slightly tweaked metric-compatible thread design that prints easily in PLA on my MakerGear M2 even with 0.25mm extrusion. The printed thread is quite shallow, but it's more than sufficient to hold the cap in.

License

The original version was distributed under the Creative Commons Attribution license. This version is GNU-GPL because the QR code generator it uses is. However, that QR code generator can be removed from the end of the OpenSCAD source without damaging any other functionality.

title: Dual J Head Carriage for Mendel

description.text:
This is an x carriage for Mendel and compatible printers that use a 50mm horizontal rod spacing and LM8UU bearings or equivalent bushings.
It is designed to use M4 hex head bolts and the aluminium mounting plates available from hotends.com for j heads from the same source. It is pretty much the same size as a standard carriage and thus is designed as a drop-in replacement. I have tried to make the design flexible and work with easily available hardware: Any belt clamp with m3/m4 holes and 10mm spacing that fits your belt will work.
No belt clamps are included, it is assumed you are upgrading from the commonly used Greg's carriage or similar: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:9869 It can be used as a bowden carriage with your favourite adapter for that, as long it has 50mm spacing between the M4 bolts with the j head centred between them. See the included picture for one way of setting this up.
I use a customized output from this openscad design to fit my setup:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1899
Basically you want to modify the script so that bolt_distance=50 and then change the nut size (hexSize=7 for M4 nut, in the coupling module) to match whatever you are threading onto the PTFE tube. It can be used with any compact direct drive extruder as long as it is designed to fit over a j head, and again has 50mm spacing between bolt holes with the j head centred. A pair of these that I modified to fit over top of a j head with the aluminum plate can be used: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:147133 Provision is provided on the carriage for a single 40mm fan at the back, between the belt mounts. This serves to assist cooling the cold-end and the printed plastic. It may also cool the hotend a bit, but it seems to work OK without a duct. I am working on designing a more specialized version with specific ducting. There are nut traps and holes for M3 nuts/bolts for fan attachment. The spacing is wide enough you can also use a 50mm fan with an adapter such as this: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:47146 Attaching a bowden extruder and choosing the lengths of M4 bolts is left as an exercise to the end user, configurations can and do vary - consider this an open platform for adapting your current setup or available hardware to a dual extrusion system. Rides on four bearings attached with zip-ties. Install all of the bolts from the bottom first, before installing the bearings.
Use strips of paper or kapton tape between the carriage and the mount plate to level the hot ends.

description.text:
UPDATE: Thank you to everyone who has favorited the model! Please give it a build if you'd like or leave a comment to see if there's anything I could improve on. They work for me but I'm totally open to alternates where available. Would a sample single print be useful for anyone to see if the holes fit for their settings?
I had a need for an Amiibo holder and saw a few novel ideas on here but nothing quite what I wanted. I measured the bases of my Amibo and did some tests. My original creation was not up to my standards and didn't offer a nice view of each tier. The one I'm offering here definitely has the 30mm per tier. Could be taller but let me know if you'd like to see a different "per tier" height.
It was designed with 123D Design. Simple, it has rounded edges and the brand "Nintendo" in the front (not using the official font or style, just a font I liked.)
Future iterations of Amiibo holders will have 4 Character "pods" with connectors, likely in the vein of Mario Brothers. A 2 tier, 6 Character version is in the works for "shelves."
Please let me know if you like it. I definitely was proud of this model.

Printer:

Wanhao Duplicator i3 v2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

2mm

Infill:

20

Notes:

I used a Grey PLA with a temp of 212 but the first row was 220. This made it difficult to remove but did allow for great adhesion and a super smooth bottom.
For the Wanhao, this takes up the majority of the build volume for the base.
The print takes under 24 hours with these settings at 40mm/s.

Self Created

First, I used digital calipers to find the base size, both circumference and height. I adjusted for tolerances and made sure the 9mm height wasn't fully realized (some Amiibos stand slightly off of their bases.)
Secondly, I began designing in 123D Design (by Autodesk; Free software). Once I had this made, I produced a single 1 character version in clear PLA to check my tolerances. Surprisingly, my first run was a 100 percent success!
Once this was done, I kept the baselines for the base and began using these measurements for all iterations.
My first 9 Character successful recreation was with Grey PLA and was the predecessor to this model. The differences are that this model has tiers 2 and 3 at 30mm higher than the previous tier, the original was 15mm. I found that you could not see the amiibos very well and it did not do a great job at highlighting individuals characters.
This style is designed to be "modern" and round while still presenting the characters as their own style.
An alternate is an 80's version I have with much more angular sides and a small block which protrudes with the words "Nintendo" inset. I also have a version with a Smash Brothers inset/protrusion.

comments.text: What about making it come apart at each tier and adding a customizer so that people who make it can customize their tiers and label or otherwise mark them for specifics?

comments.text:
I have not. I modeled this by manually measuring the base of amiibos so they fit pretty well, including depth. I would wager the Lego pieces will have some issues. Presuming they are round, they would still need to be taller than amiibo bases or there might be conflict.
If memory serves, the amiibo base diameter was 50mm, I think. Been a while since I measured.
comments.author: nleco

comments.text: I  finally printed and added images. I would suggest 15 or 12 infill. It's potentially overkill but this is a theory. 20 infill works fine. My build had issues with the spool but worked around them with minor issues. My images were from Cura slicer. I'd like to use CraftUnique but I'm still learning it. Maybe someone else can print one, eh?

I'm experimenting with a generator that I can attach windmill blades. For now, I have a handle on it, so to speak. :) It uses a 12v printer motor I scrapped and a couple 4 x 608zz bearings I had laying around. I think they were rollerblade bearings. I ended up just using a clip to on hold the top of the motor mount.

The goal is to add a couple of small 6v solar panels and turning it into a more robust and efficient system that charges a lipo and can have a light and charge a cell phone or something.

It turns out to be surprisingly efficient. With the handle, it's pretty easy to generate 3-4 volts. I connected it to the electronics from an old solar e-cig charger that has solar panel inlets, a built in white LED flashlight, a lipo battery and charging circuit. It generates enough power to operate it, as you can see in the photos. It could be made even better with a larger main gear. I think it is currently 10:1. The main gear was reaching the max size of my printer.

Next I'm on to designing some light weight blades to spin it.

description.text:
As the name suggests, the Pioneer is a 250-Size quadcopter that is built on a fully 3D-printed frame. It took multiple revisions to get it flying stable - currently its flight is comparable to a store-bought 250 frame with custom electronics.

I will provide a list of electronics I use, but keep in mind that any similar components should work. The only challenge would be that you may need to design your own platforms or mounts that attach to the main platform so that the parts fit. This is especially true for the motor arms - In the 'Post-Printing' section, I will give the dimensions for the arms' mounting holes so that you can use your own preferred CAD tool to draw up arms that fit, if you require.

You will also need to draw up a platform to mount your own power distribution board. The one I'm using is a generic board with 5V BEC and mounting holes that are identical to the CC3D flight controller.

I have uploaded the AutoCAD .dwg files for the main platform, flight controller platform, and arms, so that you can modify them to fit your own components.

Electronics Used:
-Motors: DYS BE-2204 (2400kV) brushless outrunners
-ESCs: Generic 20A brushless quadcopter ESCs
-Flight Controller: OpenPilot CC3D (now branded as LibrePilot I think)
-FPV: Generic Sony 800TVL camera, with 600mW transmitter
-Receiver: Generic 2.4GHz 6-channel
-Battery: 3s 2200mAh LiPo
-Props: 5030 tri-blade. With careful cable management, you should be able to fit 6 inch props as well.

title: 'ROCKETZ'... Interlocking Storage Stages and Fun Model
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
'ROCKETZ' are a 5 part interlocking model of a cartoon style rocket. The lower four stages are storage compartments and the top / capsule is functions as the cap for the stage below it. Refer to the images for additional information.

The largest storage capacity stage is at the base (engines) and each of the stage further up the 'ROCKETZ' reduces in capacity. The total height of 'ROCKETZ' is 235mm with all stages fitted. Be creative by printing 'ROCKETZ' in your color/s of choice... or print different stages in different colors.

Each stage lock together by aligning the lugs with the opposing parts slots, pushing the parts together then rotating 120 degrees to lock in place. This means you can carry your 'ROCKETZ' around and they won't fall apart. It also means you can access a single stage to add / remove things without opening the other stages.

'ROCKETZ' will take time to print but they are well worth the time and plastic... the result is a unique model that can be used to store away all sorts of small things from Lego / toys to nuts / bolts / screws, electronic parts / components and any other small things you need to store away.

The stages are all easy prints. No support is required. Raft is recommended for the engines and capsule in particular due to having less contact area with the build plate than stages 1 / 2 / 3.

The joint clearances have been intentionally left slightly loose to ensure most machines should be able to print this well with no issues and interlock correctly for use. If you want to uniformly scale it down 10% should be okay but any more is likely to reduce the clearances too much so the stages won't interlock.

Please refer to the print settings and images for additional information.... and post your pictures of the 'ROCKETZ' you make being put to good use.

Based on many other usable extruders but tweaked to be used with an 8mm ID Hobbed pulley mounted on a 50mm X 8MM hex bolt. Works well with PLA or ABS 3mm filament.
I don't use a herringbone gear because that would mean complete dissassembly to get to the filament. In my design the Nylock nut on the back side can be removed and the large gear with the hobbed pulley can be removed very easily for clearing/cleaning after a "spinout"

Designed in house at Van-Isle-Rapid-Prototyping after many iterations this is the easiest and most reliable extruder I have ever used. The design is meant to make it extremely easy to:
  • Change color in the middle of a print by "pausing" your LCD panel.
  • Clear a jam
  • Overall Build Time very low.
    • There are two fans as well as a 5mm LED light connected to the D9 12volt outputs from a RAMPS board. One fan cools the barrel of the J-Head hot end and the other cools the stepper motor. VIRP-V3 EXTRUDER ASSY
    Parts List:
    Vitamins: QTY
    M3 nylock nut 1
    M3 washer 6
    M3 x 6mm grub screw 1
    M3 x 10mm SH screw 4
    M3 x 16mm SH screw 2
    M3 x 20mm SH screw 2
    M3 x 30mm SH screw 1
    M3 x 35mm SH screw 1
    M8 Nylocking nut 1
    M8 washer 4
    M8 x 50mm Hex Bolt 1
    M8 x 28mm threaded rod 1
    608zz brgs 3
    Limit Switch 1
    J-Head MK-IV B Hot-end 1
    12v Brushless 40mm Fan 2
    40mm Heatsink 1
    5mm LED+470ohm res 1
    JST 10 wire quick plug 1
    JST 2 wire quick plug 1
    Ty-wraps small 5
    Nema-17 Stepper Mtr 1
    Fold Back Binder Clip 1 Tools Required:
    Drill
    Standard wiring and soldering tools
    M2.5 Allan wrench
    3mm tap
    3mm drill bit
    3.3mm drill bit
    5 mm drill bit Assembly Instructions
    Front side is considered the side that the gears are installed on
    This extruder has a carriage assy that is setup for 50mm wide linear 8mm rod otherwise just use screw holes provided
    Support material is already incorporated into design
    Using this gear set the stepper steps per unit for extruder should be set to around 470
  • Remove support material from VIRP-V3 Extruder MB (Main Body)(Fig. 1)
  • Tap 3mm holes in
    a. VIRP-V3 Extruder MB
    i. Front side of hot end retaining screws (2 places) only tap half depth
    ii. R/H Extruder carriage attachment screws (2 Places) under stepper motor
  • Drill 3mm holes in
    a. VIRP-V2 Extruder MB
    i. Back side Hot-end retaining screw holes(1/2 way)
    b. Limit switch
    i. 2 holes
    c. Belt Clamp-INF
    i. 2 holes
    d. Small Extruder Gear-INF Grub screw hole
  • Drill 3.3mm (tolerance) holes
    a. VIRP-V2 Extruder MB
    i. L/H side @ Limit switch mount holes
  • Drill 5mm Hole in Small Extruder Gear-INF Shaft hole
  • Insert M8x28mm threaded rod into 608zz brg snap into place on EXT BRG Clamp-INF
  • Grind or file a flat spot on stepper shaft @ the base(not reqd if your stepper is a D-Cut shaft)
  • Cut off center terminal of limit switch
  • Feed Limit Switch wires through channels
  • Install Pre-Built J-Head (w/wiring 60cm for resistor 40cm for thermistor)using (1) M3x30mm SH screw + washer from the back side & 1 M3 x 35mm through fan mount hole from backside
  • Install 5mm LED with resistor(470ohm mount on the neg(shorter) leg)/wires (30cm length) Cement in place
  • Neatly ty-wrap wires up-between mtr and drive housing
  • Install Nema-17 Stepper Motor using (4) M3x10mm SH screws + washers placing wire exit at the side
  • Solder all wires to JST10 and JST2 plugs following wiring diagram
  • Build up Large extruder gear/hobbed pulley assy
    a. Insert M8x50 hex bolt(grind or file a flat at the thread/smooth transition area for grub screw seat on the shank) through Large Extruder gear
    b. Stack (4) M8 washers onto bolt against large printed gear
    c. Install 608zz brg
    d. Install and tighten hobbed pulley with grub farthest from large pulley, run a piece of 3mm filament through extruder assy to ensure proper alignment.
  • Install Large extruder gear/hobbed pulley assy into VIRP-V2 Extruder MB
  • Install 608zz brg into back side(for alignment)
  • Install M3 nylock nut into Small Extruder Gear-INF(I recommend you run a 3mm bolt through the nylock first just to break it in)
  • Install M3x6mm grub screw into Small Extruder Gear-INF
  • Install Small Extruder Gear-INF onto Stepper shaft, tighten grub into flat spot
  • Mesh gears so there is virtually no backlash, rotate gears to ensure no hard spots, tighten outer two screw on mtr.
  • Remove Large gear assy
  • Tighten inner two motor screws
  • Install Large gear assy
  • Install M8 Nylocking nut on large gear assy do not overtighten. Gears should still turn easily
  • Install 40mm heatsink on top of stepper motor (glue or double sided tape)
  • Install 40mm fan onto heatsink using M3 x 16mm screws in diametrically opposed holes

title: Wanhao Duplicator i3 v2 bed spring cap

description.text:
Caps for the bottom of the springs in the Wanhao Duplicator i3 v2.
I had noticed that bed leveling was a pain and noticed some of the issues were the springs on the bottom didn't stay straight with the top.
The top is held by the protruding bolt, but outside of another bolt at the bottom, or an overly constructed part, I didn't have an immediate answer.
The answer came to me as a cap with a hole in it. The spring fits perfectly inside and the hole in the center is good enough to fit through. They add 1mm or so to the base and keep the spring from sliding. The washer still goes on the bottom. The spring is kept still by the hole in the center and the uniform inset it is placed in.
Originally designed to enclose both top and bottom, this is NOT advised. It is best if the top is left held by the bolt above.

There are also two choices in knobs, the large knurled knob (50mm in diameter), and the smaller knurled knob (20mm in diameter).

The fully assembled version will allow your acrylic sheets to lay flush with the outer surface of the extrusion when held in place with magnets and hinge open to just over 90 degrees.

description.text:
After stumbling across the design for a cool looking trout on the CNC Forum by mhackney, I have been wanting to print a fishing game for my kids for a while.

I finally spent the time to print off a whole lot of them as well as create a simple fishing rod and lure to use with them.

Both my little kids are enjoying playing with them. Hope someone else finds them useful.

Printer Brand:

SeeMeCNC

Printer:

Rostock MAX

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Infill:

20%

Notes:

Printed in PLA with no support. Should be simple to print.

The fish are printed with 0 solid top and bottom layers and using a variety of infill patterns to create different fish. They scale well from 0.7 to 1.5 to create a variety of different sized fishes. (Daddy/Mummy and brother fishes according to my little boy).

The lure and rod are printed with 20% infill. Watch the height of the rod as it may be too high for some printers. Can always be cut in half and glued together.

The lure has a small square hole at the bottom which will take a 3mm x 3mm x 3mm magnet. It does not need support when you print it as it has an angled top. The magnet was a tight fit on mine so used a flat piece of metal (well a hammer) to press it in. If it is loose on yours please glue it in otherwise it will come out.

You need a couple things besides the 3D printed parts....

3mm x 3mm x 3mm Magnet - I used Rare Earth Neodymium Magnets N35 3mm x 3mm x 3mm (search on ebay). I had a whole lot of them lying around from another project. They work great and can take the weight of the fish up to 1.5 scale easily.

Metal washers for the eyes - I had a number of them left over from another project. Any small metal washers will probably work. If you really want to, you could use different sized ones depending on the size of the fish so they look better as eyes.

Glue - Used Fast setting Epoxy glue for the eyes which worked well.

String - To tie the lure to the rod - A fairly short piece of string worked well for me.

title: Compact Bowden Extruder, direct drive 1.75mm for Tevo Tarantula

description.text: A compact direct drive bowden extruder for 1.75mm and a MK8 style hobbed pulley. This is mirrored so it fits the Tevo Tarantula printer

Instructions 
  Use 2mm drill to clean filament path on base plate.
Use M5(or M6 if using stock) screw tap to cut thread for push-fit bowden connector on base plate and bearing holder on idler.
Attach push-fit bowden connector(s) on base plate.
Attach 608zz bearing to idler and secure it with a M5 washer and a M5x10mm allen head screw. If you are using the alternative idler insert the 608 bearing between idler parts and secure it with a M5x14mm allen head screw.
Attach NEMA17-Motor with three M3x8mm allen head screws (use countersunk holes).
Attach idler to base plate with a M3x16mm allen head screw. Avoid to much tension to allow idler moving freely.
Fasten hobbed pulley on NEMA17 stepper motor shaft. Adjust its height accordingly.
Insert Filament into extruder.
Insert M3 nut into base plate slot.
Use M3 allen head screw of suitable length with washers and a spring to apply pressure on filament.
Happy extruding ;-)

RT Whipletree wants to distribute the tension force between 4 fingers (not thumb), to improve the grip (THIS IS A BETA, PLEASE SHARE YOUR EXPERIENCE).

How to paste depends on the material with which you are printing. If you use PLA the best glue is chloroform, if you use ABS the best glue is acetone. description.text:
There´s a better version at http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1571739

Sorry for my bad english ;)

The right luggage holder on my BMW was broken. Looking for spare I had the idea to construct the holder as a clamp. The case must be held tight , but can also degrade rapidly .
Assembly:
The luggage holder is glued to the trunk and then additionally secured with rivets or screws . Subsequently, the cover plate is glued over it.
The case is then clicked on the tube holder . The locking ring is about also built on the holder and then pushed down into the small recess of the luggage holder ... finished...

+++ the nose of the locking-ring should be a little bit longer, I'll make ab better one +++

Der rechte Kofferhalter an meiner BMW war gebrochen. Auf der Suche nach Ersatz hatte ich die Idee, den Halter als Klampe zu konstruieren. Der Koffer muss sicher halten, sich aber auch schnell abbauen lassen.
Zusammenbau:
Der Kofferhalter wird mit dem Koffer verklebt und dann mit Nieten oder Schrauben zusätzlich gesichert. Anschließend wird die Abdeckplatte darüber geklebt.
Der Koffer wird dann an den Rohrhalter geklickt. Der Sicherungsring wird darüber ebenfalls an den Halter gebaut und dann nach unten in die kleine Aussparung des Kofferhalters geschoben ... fertig
